  "target_response": {
    "text": "Since your duration looks reasonable — last night's log shows 7.3 hours — the grogginess is more likely about quality and timing than quantity. A few levers tend to matter most. Keep your bed and wake times inside the same one-hour window every day, including weekends; an erratic schedule produces exactly the groggy-despite-enough-sleep feeling you're describing. Cut caffeine after midday and alcohol close to bedtime, since both fragment sleep even when total time looks fine. Get outside light soon after waking to anchor your body clock. One caveat: your sleep is hand-logged, so time in bed and time actually asleep may differ more than the number suggests. Try fixing the schedule window first for two weeks and note the groggy mornings in your log; that record will tell us which lever to pull next.",
